<p><strong>.gov is government’s first line of defense</strong> in cutting through all the security noise. <img src="/assets/img/icons/flexed-biceps.png" alt="Flexed biceps icon" title="Flexed biceps icon" /></p>

<p><strong>.gov verifies you’re legit</strong>, because only official government entities can get a .gov. <img src="/assets/img/icons/classical-building.png" alt="Classical building icon" title="Classical building icon" /> <img src="/assets/img/icons/check-mark.png" alt="Check mark icon" title="Check mark icon" /></p>

<p><strong>We need all governments</strong> – local and national – <strong>to show we’re united</strong> and <strong>not messing around</strong> anymore when it comes to <strong>keeping Americans safe online</strong>. <img src="/assets/img/icons/flag-us.png" alt="U.S. flag icon" title="U.S. flag icon" /> <img src="/assets/img/icons/locked.png" alt="Locked icon" title="Locked icon" /></p>

<p>If every government website in America was .gov, the general public would know:</p>

<p><strong>“I’m on a government website. I trust this. They’ve got my back. I’m good to go.”</strong> <img src="/assets/img/icons/flag-us.png" alt="U.S. flag icon" title="U.S. flag icon" /> <img src="/assets/img/icons/heart-hands.png" alt="Heart hands icon" title="Heart hands icon" /></p>

<p>We know what you’re thinking:</p>

<p><strong>“This totally makes sense. We’re going .gov ASAP. What do we do now?”</strong> <img src="/assets/img/icons/thinking-face.png" alt="Thinking face icon" title="Thinking face icon" /></p>

<p>Here’s the <strong>.gov 411</strong>. <img src="/assets/img/icons/details.png" alt="Details icon" title="Details icon" /></p>

<p>The <strong><a href="https://home.dotgov.gov/">DotGov</a></strong> program is the service <strong>U.S. government entities use to get and manage their .gov domains</strong>. <img src="/assets/img/icons/cursor.png" alt="Cursor icon" title="Cursor icon" /></p>

<p>This includes:</p>

<p><strong>Federal, state, local, territorial governments</strong> or other <strong>publicly controlled entities</strong>.</p>

<p><strong>Tribal governments</strong> recognized by the U.S. government (federal or state).</p>

<p><strong><a href="https://home.dotgov.gov/">DotGov</a></strong> is managed by the U.S. Department of Homeland Security’s <strong><a href="https://www.cisa.gov/">Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency</a></strong> (AKA <strong><a href="https://www.cisa.gov/">CISA</a></strong>). <img src="/assets/img/icons/flag-us.png" alt="U.S. flag icon" title="U.S. flag icon" /> <img src="/assets/img/icons/locked.png" alt="Locked icon" title="Locked icon" /></p>

<p>And you know if they’re in charge, <strong>they’re not messing around</strong>.</p>

<p>Does your <strong>government website need a .gov ASAP</strong>? <img src="/assets/img/icons/eyes.png" alt="Eyes icon" title="Eyes icon" /></p>

<p><strong>If yes,</strong> show your community <strong>you’re .gov united</strong>, and that <strong>you’re not messing around</strong>. <img src="/assets/img/icons/collision.png" alt="Collision icon" title="Collision icon" /></p>

